<HEAD>DOT Reconsidering Cutback In Rural Air Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Transportion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is taking a second look at a plan it introduced last month that would force some small airlines to eliminate unprofitable routes in sparsely populated areas. <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION> cited budget restraints when it proposed sharply curtailing its `` Essential Air Service'' program. Under the program, the federal government subsidizes flights to and from about 150 small cities that would probably not otherwise have air service because the routes are not moneymakers. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Paris </PERSON> said an announcement could be made as early as the beginning of next week about changes in the <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION> plan. He would not elaborate, but another department official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said: `` There is something under consideration. There is movement to responding to a congressional request.'' He added, `` Nothing has been signed yet, and it's not a decision until somebody signs it.'' The original proposal was swiftly attacked by lawmakers from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and other states that would be especially hard hit. Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said the reductions would be `` a fatal blow'' to the economic growth efforts of some communities, and Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Kan </LOCATION>., said the plan could mean the end of commuter air service in The original DOT action was in response to a $ 6.6 million shortfall in the air service program's appropriation for the 1989 fiscal year. The department proposed four likely plans for coping with the cuts. One of them, considered the harshest by some, would cut 53 cities entirely out of the program. One-third of those cities are more than 100 miles from the next nearest airport. In defending the cuts, the department has pointed to little-used flights that receive subsidies in remote areas. For example, the government spent $ 379,000 in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> last year to keep flights going between <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moultrie </LOCATION> that averaged one passenger. The route would probably be eliminated if the subsidy ends. But <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON> said ending subsidies to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> cities could do more than simply inconvenience passengers who would have to travel to another airport further away. `` For rural areas, there is a direct link between adequate air service and economic development,'' <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON> said. `` One of the first questions business leaders ask when they come to look at rural areas is: ` What's the air service like?''' In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the cutbacks could mean the end of flights in and out of <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Clarksburg-Fairmont </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Elkins </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Morgantown </LOCATION>. In releasing the plan on Dec. 14, the <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION> said it hoped it could take effect on March 1, following a public comment period. <ORGANIZATION> Exec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which operates in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said in a letter to Rep. <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Leath </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>: `` From our standpoint, any cut in the <ORGANIZATION> Essential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> program would be devastating. Exec Express II has been rebuilding air service in communities which have not had adequate service in the past.''
