<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> are challenging subpoenas from <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, while prosecutors say <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s continued demand to use classified information is an effort to torpedo his upcoming trial on charges stemming from the Iran-Contra affair. The government filed a motion in federal court Friday to quash the subpoenas for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, whose testimony is being sought by <PERSON> North </PERSON> as part of the fired <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide's defense. Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said <PERSON> North </PERSON> `` has not made the requisite showing of relevance, materiality and need for specifically identified information that he seeks to obtain'' from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said that in accordance with an offer made last Sept. 28, the president will consider furnishing appropriate information with written answers to `` reasonable written questions'' from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` joins that offer.'' <PERSON> North </PERSON> served the subpoenas Dec. 22. `` The spectacle of a former or sitting President being subjected to peremptory judicial process may chill foreign governments in the way they deal with the President now and in the future,'' the government said in the motion to quash the subpoenas for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to appear at the trial. North's lawyers, meanwhile, served the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> with subpoenas for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to turn over various personal papers for use by the defense, said department spokesman <PERSON> Loye </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. Earlier in the day, <LOCA