<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Outgoing Commerce Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON> says many American products are below world standards of quality and the Japanese are two years ahead in developing salable products from American inventions. Blaming antitrust laws for a large part of the problem, <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> urged President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to prepare for `` economic warfare'' in the 1990s. `` What's going to be on the top burner of the 1990s for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is trading, and how is <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> going to make sure it will be the number one player,'' <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said Friday in a last speech for `` Export Now,'' a campaign he has pressed in his 18 months in office. As President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> retires next week, <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> will follow. An old friend of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> from the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil industry, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>, has been named to succeed him. `` The reason that many American products are not selling abroad is very simple: because they do n't have sufficient quality to do it,'' he said. He told how his family company, <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, had been a big supplier of sheet steel to the American auto industry, but had to work five years to produce steel that would meet the standards of <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, the Japanese auto-maker. <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> says antitrust laws discourage cooperation of American companies, creating a barrier to more effective competition. `` It -LRB- should -RRB- be possible for high technology companies or other companies to get together, not only just research together, but develop and produce together and market together and then compete,'' he said. `` That's what has to happen if we're going to stay in some very important markets including the semiconductor market ... or high definition television, or super-conductivity, and there's much more coming down the path.'' This country has some marvelous technology, but it is less expert at transforming theoretical discoveries into products that can sell, he complained. `` The Japanese can do this two years quicker than we can,'' he said. `` This is a serious problem if we develop a technology but if the Japanese take our technology and use it and we're two years delayed in getting into the marketplace ... That's going to be disastrous to this country.'' <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION>'s criticism of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry was not the first from a high figure in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, who was deputy to former <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, has criticized what he called a `` corpocracy'' in American business for what he saw as lack of initiative. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> is to be secretary of State under President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> will head the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>.
