<HEAD>Customs Official Says Destination Of Nerve Gas May Never Be Known</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities have identified <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as a possible destination for a planned illegal shipment of nerve gas, but the final arrival point may never be known, a <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> official said. `` We do n't have to know -LRB- it -RRB- to make a case'' against two men charged Thursday with trying to export the deadly gas, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercier </PERSON>, head customs investigator in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>. Prosecutors must only prove that the Korean-American and British business men tried to circumvent licensing requirements in exporting restricted materials, he said Friday. The charge carries a maximum five-year prison term and a $ 250,000 fine. `` I'm hopeful that through investigation, or whatever else,'' the destination would be positively determined, <PERSON> Mercier </PERSON> said. But he pointed out that the deal never went through. `` It's not as though there's a trail for us to follow,'' he said. Authorities said Friday they are trying to learn the identities of two other people accused of plotting with the suspects. <PERSON> Juwhan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yun </PERSON>, 48, was arrested Thursday at what he thought would be a meeting with an arms supplier, who was actually a <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> undercover agent. He has been ordered jailed pending a bail hearing Tuesday on charges of conspiring to illegally export sarin, a nerve gas. An arrest warrant was issued for <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> businessman who authorities said was seeking to obtain the gas _ $ 5 million worth in the form of 500 quarter-ton bombs _ from <PERSON> Yun </PERSON>. The possibility of his extradition is being studied, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prosecutors said. The complaint filed in federal court accusing <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> and <PERSO