<SECOND>PM-US News Case,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Ruling Against US News Retirees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 200 retirees of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; World Report have lost another round in their court claim that they were underpaid $ 100 million in profit-sharing benefits. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> on Friday upheld a lower court decision that said the retirees were paid a fair value for their company stock before 1982, even though employees who held stock when the news magazine was sold two years later received much more per share. The 230 plaintiffs, who retired between 1974 and 1982, were paid an average of $ 100 a share, said their attorney, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Raywid </PERSON>. The magazine's 1984 employees got $ 2,842 a share when <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> was sold, according to court papers. `` We think the opinion is wrong,'' said <PERSON> Raywid </PERSON>, who added there is a `` substantial likelihood'' it will be appealed. The three-member court effectively said companies `` can sacrifice the interests of past employees and retirees'' to benefit current and future employees and maintain employee ownership, he said. Under the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> profit-sharing plan, when an employee retired the company could exercise its option to buy the employee's stock shares. According to court papers, employees who retired in 1973 received $ 65 a share, while the value rose to $ 470 for those who retired in 1981. The magazine was sold for $ 176 million in 1984 to media and real estate magnate <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuckerman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Raywid </PERSON> said the plaintiffs had received a total of $ 5.5 million for their stock but believed they would have gotten $ 100 million more if they had been given full value. The plaintiffs contended the company that appraised the magazine's value improperly classified retirees' stock as a minority interest rather than a majority interest, which would have carried a higher premium. In addition, the plaintiffs said the appraiser placed an unfairly low value on property <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> owned in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the decision to give the retirees' stock a minority status, saying it was `` entirely consistent'' with the profit-sharing plan's rules and with federal law. The court also affirmed the property valuation, saying much of the land was being used as a parking lot and development had not been expected at the time. A major objective of the profit-sharing plan was the perpetuation of employee ownership, the appellate court said, adding that the law does not set an exclusive goal of maximizing benefits. `` The plaintiffs were not the only beneficiaries of the plan,'' the judges said. `` Indeed, the worst that can be said of the plan is that it was administered to favor a rolling class of future beneficiaries over those present and past.'' Ruling in the case were Circuit Judges <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>.
