<HEAD>Report Urges Colleges To Expand Study-Abroad Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fearing a loss of the nation's competitive edge, a group of college officials is seeking ways to double the number of students studying abroad and include more business and science majors. Members of the Council on <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> met privately in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Friday to discuss ways to expand study-abroad opportunities for less-affluent youngsters and encourage students to attend programs in places other than just <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The meeting followed release of a council report in December which found fewer than 5 percent, or about 50,000, of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> college students studying abroad each year, while some 350,000 foreign students attend <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools. `` Citizens of other nations are learning more about us than we are about them and each year are doing so in increasing numbers,'' said the 28-page report, `` Educating for Global Competence.'' `` We have quite rightly welcomed these students to our own shores but have failed to encourage our own students to go abroad,'' it said. The report warned that failure to expand study-abroad opportunities would mean `` we will irreversibly diminish the world status of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodbury </PERSON>, chancellor of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> system, said in an interview that the council decided to establish a Committee on Unrepresented Groups to help schools develop study-abroad opportunities for such groups as business and law students, and poor and minority youngsters. `` We plan to get poor students better information on what the costs are,'' <PERSON> Woodbury </PERSON> said after the meeting. `` There's a common belief that study-abroad progams will cost more. In fact, many programs do not involve extra cost.'' According to the report, only 3 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> high school graduates and 5 percent of college graduates have meaningful proficiency in a second language. Thirty-three states do n't require foreign language study in high school, and 34 states do n't require world history. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is one of the few industrialized countries where students can graduate from college without studying a foreign language. `` If you look at the attitude of colleges here, international study has never been a very big part of the curriculum. It's just a ` good thing to do,' rather than a part of the mainstream,'' said <PERSON> Woodbury </PERSON>. The majority of students studying abroad are white, affluent females from highly educated families, according to the report. Most are liberal arts majors and spend less than six months in foreign programs. Relatively few students majoring in business, public health, science or math take part in such programs, said the report. <PERSON> Woodbury </PERSON> said his own school started an exchange program with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1987 involving 15 Soviet and 15 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students each year. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> system is also trying to establish an exchange program in which business students could work as interns in Japanese companies, he said. The council, established in 1947, is a non-profit organization based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> which fosters student exchange programs. Former <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulbright </PERSON> serves as honorary chairman.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Copies of the report are available for free from the Council, Department G, 205 East 42nd Street, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> 10017.
