<HEAD>Cross-Wiring Check Ordered For Boeing 757s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cross-wiring found in cargo hold emergency systems of two <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757 airliners prompted federal aviation authorities to order inspections of all the aircraft within the next three days. The order late Friday was similar to one issued for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s 48 hours earlier involving critical engine fire and vibration warning systems. The two `` airworthiness directives'' were unrelated, however. The earlier order was prompted by speculation the pilot of a British <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> 737 that crashed Sunday, killing 44 people, might have been confused by false wiring into shutting down his only good engine. The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> reported Friday, however, that investigators were certain there was no wiring problem, and neither <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nor British airline officials reported finding such a problem on any other aircraft. Tests of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 737s have to be completed by Sunday morning. The latest `` airworthiness directive'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> gives airlines 72 hours to check whether cross-wiring in cargo holds might cause sprinklers to go on in the wrong cargo area in the event of a fire. The problem had been discovered in two of the aircraft, said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON>. He said no details were available on how the problem was found or on which airliners, but he said neither involved an actual fire or accident. The order involving 757s `` is not really relevant to the British crash except that the subject is also miswiring,'' <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said 205 of the 757s are in service worldwide, with 119 of them used by four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines: <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>. `` The miswiring means that if the flight crew got a warning indicating a fire in the forward cargo compartment and pushed the button to activate the fire extinguishing system for that compartment, it would activate the system in the aft cargo compartment,'' and vice-versa, said an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> statement. The checks were not expected to disrupt any scheduled flights.
