<HEAD>Defense Rests In Trial Of Man Accused In Daughter's Beating Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The defense rested in the murder trial of <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, accused of beating to death his illegally adopted 6-year-old daughter, without introducing an insanity defense and without calling him to testify. During 11 weeks of testimony, the jury heard 39 prosecution witnesses and 13 defense witnesses. State Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> scheduled the defense summation for next Thursday. He told the jurors the government would sum up next Friday and they would get the case on Jan. 23 after receiving the judge's instructions. With the jury absent, <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> again asked <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s lawyers, <LOCATION> Ira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> DiLuzio </PERSON>, `` Am I correct you do not intend to introduce an insanity defense?'' `` You are 100 percent correct, your honor,'' DiLuzio replied. <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> had repeatedly pressed <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s lawyers to tell him if they intended to argue that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> was not responsible for <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s death by reason of mental defect or disease. In case they did, the judge had ordered the defendant to be examined by a prosecution psychiatrist to determine his mental condition on Nov. 1, 1987, the night he is accused of fatally beating <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. The examination was completed Thursday night. The judge said if the defense made any reference in their summation next week to <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> being motivated by `` cults, staring, or that he heard electronic mousetraps in the walls of his apartment'' that would be tantamount to introducing an insanity defense. If that happened, the judge said, he would reopen the trial and let the prosecution psychiatrist testify. The decision by the defense not to use an insanity defense leaves the jury with a circumstantial case in which no one said they saw <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> killed. <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s former live-in companion, testified that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> told her he struck <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> because the child was `` staring at him and trying to place him in a hypnotic trance.'' Both <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, 46, were charged with second-degree murder for `` depraved indifference'' to <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s life. Charges against Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> were dismissed in October, at the request of the prosecution, which says she was too battered and emotionally crippled to harm <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>, but the defense challenges that contention. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> told reporters outside the courtroom that the prosecution had not proved beyond a reasonable doubt that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, 47, a disbarred lawyer, inflicted the injuries that killed <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. He continued to suggest that the injuries could have been inflicted by Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>. `` We hope that issue has been squarely raised and will be considered'' by the jury, he said.
