Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The Soviet side confirmed its full support for the Afghan leadership's policies and said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will continue extending the Republic of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> all-round assistance under treaties and agreements concluded by the two countries,'' the news agency said. Since the Soviets committed themselves to an Afghan withdrawal, they have transferred millions of dollars worth of armaments and military supplies to their <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> allies, Western observers say. The Afghan government and the Soviets blame the guerrillas for continuing hostilities because they have refused to join a cease-fire proclaimed by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> on Jan. 1. Soviet troops marched into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to preside over the replacement of one Marxist leader by another, and the 100,000 soldiers stayed on to prop up the government against a nationwide insurgency.
