<HEAD>Univeristy to Decide if Heir Can Use 133-year-old Scholarship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even back when a loaf of bread cost a couple of cents, it must have seemed like a bargain: Contribute $ 100, and your sons, your grandsons, your great-grandsons, and so on in perpetuity would get free tuition at <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Sixty-eight people took the school up on its offer back in 1856, and a descendant of one of them is trying to get the school to make good on the deal. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Raper </PERSON> is the first descendant of state Rep. <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Abel </PERSON>, one of the purchasers, to try to benefit from his great-great-great-great-grandfather's investment. However, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> residents now pay about $ 1,100 a semester, not $ 8 as in 1856, and the university is studying how it will handle the family's claim. University counsel <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> says he will review the request when he gets copies of wills and documents that establish a line of succession for the scholarship. <PERSON> Raper </PERSON>, a 1988 graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Owen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Spencer </LOCATION>, is majoring in business at <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, a state university that was founded in 1820. His mother, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Raper </PERSON>, said last week she has the documents <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> says he needs, and threatened to sue the university if the scholarship is not honored. Mrs. <PERSON> Raper </PERSON> said she has known about the scholarship since she was a little girl, but considered the piece of paper as just a curiosity until a year ago. Previous generations of <PERSON> Abel </PERSON>'s descendants either did n't go to school or included no sons. The scholarship specifies male descendants because women were not admitted to the school back when it was created. Mrs. <PERSON> Raper </PERSON> said when her mother died a year ago and her son was making plans to attend <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, the significance of the scholarship hit her. She consulted a lawyer, and decided to follow up on it. `` It's something that my great-great-great grandfather purchased in the belief that his heirs would be taken care of,'' she said. `` He was a supporter of the university, and I'm sure $ 100 helped tremendously at that time.'' If the validity of the scholarship has to be decided in court, <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> says, it would be the first time. He said similar requests have come up a few times over the decades. But for at least 40 years they have been rejected for in-state residents on the basis of a university ruling that technically, nobody from <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> pays tuition, only `` fees.'' Out-of-state residents are eligible for partial scholarships _ the difference between in-state `` fees'' and whatever the total charged to out-of-state residents is, the ruling stated. Whether that definition will be applied in <PERSON> Raper </PERSON>'s case, in order to disqualify him, is what university officials are trying to decide. But Mrs. <PERSON> Raper </PERSON> said her great-great-great grandfather would not have purchased a perpetual scholarship if it were only intended to pay out-of-state tuition. `` I just ca n't understand why he'd purchase something that would be no good to him,'' she said.
