 The last president to hold an open house was <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, 80 years ago. But the most memorable occasion was in 1829, when thousands of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> frontiersmen and Indian fighters in muddy boots followed one of their own, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, right into the White House. Many stood on the pastel upholsteries of fine damask and satin just to get a better view; others shattered china and glassware after too much refreshment. Most new presidents, of course, would prefer that their inaugurals be remembered, not for the whirlwind of celebration, but for their calls to the nation's conscience, those ringing words of wisdom to set <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> on an ever brighter course. But there have been more thuds, than rings, especially in this century. Still, the nation embraces with special fondness the words of <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Delano </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> to a Depression-stricken country in 1933: `` The only thing we have to fear is fear itself.'' And then there were those of a Democrat from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, who unlike <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, managed to defeat an incumbent vice president for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. `` Ask not ...'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> probably will have his moments. But first he may want, simply, to take in the view. The departing tenant, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, put it this way, by way of defining the job <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has had the last eight years: `` The vice presidency ... is described by an old rule of dog-sledding _ only the lead dog gets a change of scenery.''
