beginning of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, the challenge and opportunity of our future. We are challenged to protect our nation's security while we pursue the opportunity for peace with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. We are challenged to end the plague of drugs and crime, while we endeavor to provide opportunity for our young people to become educated, and trained to join our workforce. We are challenged to reduce the federal deficit while opening opportunities for those afflicted with disease or burdened by poverty. But perhaps our greatest new challenge in the years ahead will come from the natural environment that delimits our world and defines the quality of our lives. When the pilgrim <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Winthrop </PERSON> envisioned the shining city upon the hill, of which the president speaks so eloquently, he looked out upon a continent untouched by smog, hazardous waste and acid rain. In the centuries since that pristine age, we have conquered the continent, but we have also made it dirty and unsafe. The industrial revolution has swept the world, but we have n't swept up behind it Now the decades of neglect have come back to haunt us, and threaten to engulf our children's future, and endanger their health and safety. If we do not meet this challenge, we may face disaster. Holes in the ozone layer and acid in the rain will cause skin cancer and lung disease. Gases in the air will warm the planet and lead to drought in our heartland and flooding along our coast. Waste in our water will make our beaches forbidding places to visit on a summer's day. But there is hope, and it lies, as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would say, with `` we the people.'' The protection of the environment will be high on the agenda of the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the new president not because it makes political sense, but because the people know it makes common sense. People like <PERSON> Rico </P