<HEAD>Afghans Glad to Bid Adieu to Soviets, But Worried About Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Standing stoically in line for heating fuel, <PERSON> Sadrahmah </PERSON> <PERSON> Bikhar </PERSON> mused on the pullout of Soviet troops, saying simply, `` It's good; I do n't like them.'' It's hard to find anyone who does on the streets of this bleak capital ringed by snowy hills. In random interviews with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, most people were openly hostile toward the Soviets. But asked about the survival prospects of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s Marxist government, many glanced uneasily at the interpreter and bystanders and make noncommittal replies. Instead, they expressed hope _ but little belief _ that the fighting will end when the Soviets leave. Their reluctance to answer certain questions is understandable. In this divided land, official rhetoric remains upbeat, although it contrasts sharply with reality. On Saturday, anti-government guerrillas, known as <ORGANIZATION> Mujahadeen </ORGANIZATION>, attacked a 400-vehicle government supply and ammunition convoy four miles from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Western reporters saw Afghan units dig in on both sides of the Solang highway, a key northern route, and heard rocket fire before government troops opened fire into the hills and the convoy raced past. The same day, the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> published new triumphant exhortations from the Soviet-backed Marxist administration. In a report on celebrations for the ninth anniversary of the founding of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, it said Gen. <PERSON> Ghulam </PERSON> <PERSON> Farouq </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaqubi </PERSON> welcomed <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, declaring, `` We feel ourselves more powerful than ever against the thievish attacks of the intransigent extremists.'' On the streets, <PERSON> Bikhar </PERSON>'s several-hour wait reflected the increasing harassment of the convoys running three times a week on the Solang, now the sole highway supplying the city. As the Soviets have moved out their forces to meet a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> deadline for pulling out all their troops by Feb. 15, guerrillas have approached the capital and stepped up convoy attacks. <PERSON> Bikhar </PERSON> said all he knew was that things were getting worse. Asked what he thought would happen when all the Soviets were gone, he shrugged and said through an interpreter, `` I do n't know. I hope the fighting will stop.'' But there was no doubt in the mind of <LOCATION> Eshaqza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Anargul </LOCATION>, a mechanic with the state-owned Afghan Airline, <PERSON> Ariana </PERSON>. `` There will be fighting for another 10 years, maybe longer,'' he said. `` Economically, it will get worse too,'' he added. Armed opposition to the government began soon after it invited the Soviet troops in 1979 in the wake of a Soviet-backed coup. Since then, the war has killed an estimated 1 million people, driven a third of the 15 million Afghans to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and scarred millions more. Amputees are a common sight on the streets of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Tales abound of family members _ troops, guerrillas, and civilians _ killed or missing. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Salom </PERSON>, a turbaned 60-year-old, said he fled his village of <LOCATION> Saraikhoga </LOCATION>, 50 miles from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, after it was damaged in bombing attacks against rebels. He has squeezed into a mud house with relatives in the <LOCATION> Kharkhana </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The area is a mixture of bleak, concrete six-story apartments and slums of mud houses without heat, electricity or water. <PERSON> Salom </PERSON> squats under a blanket in a friend's shop _ a cargo container turned into a makeshift store selling soap, nails, and other items. He is one of about 1 million refugees who have doubled the prewar population of the capital. `` We just want peace,'' he said. `` No Russians, no <ORGANIZATION> Mujahadeen </ORGANIZATION>, no government, just peace.''
