<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s joint celebration Monday of the birthdays of two Confederate generals and a black civil rights leader on Lee-Jackson-King Day is `` the perfect combination of diversity,'' says the man responsible for the merger. Lt. Gov. <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, who as a state senator five years ago pushed through the bill making <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Day a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> holiday, says he does n't find it ironic that King shares the holiday with <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> natives <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> `` Stonewall'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` I find no irony in it at all,'' <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, a grandson of slaves and the first black elected to statewide office in the South since Reconstruction, said Friday. `` It shows we are prepared to recognize good men. Men of principle have differed on principle and I think all three were men of principle.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, a civil rights leader who worked with <PERSON> King </PERSON>, said Saturday that <PERSON> King </PERSON> deserves a day all his own because `` <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> stood alone as a giant.'' But he said King would have been amused at being linked with heroes of the Confederacy. `` Dr. <PERSON> King </PERSON> was very tolerant of things like that,'' <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said. `` If he is looking down from heaven now I can hear him laughing.'' The bill passed the state legislature in 1984 after seven years of effort by <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> and often acrimonious debate in public hearings. Opponents objected to honoring a non-Virginian with a holiday when favorite sons such as <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patrick </PERS