<HEAD>``Saturday's Will Never Seem The Same,'' President Says In Last Radio
Talk</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts graf 7, ``Several hours xxx to update with departure
for Camp David</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> delivered his 331st, and last, radio address as president on Saturday, telling his listeners he was grateful to have played a part in `` the story of a people and a cause ... the American saga.'' `` Believe me, Saturdays will never seem the same. I'll miss you,'' the president said as he read his five-minute address from the Oval Office. `` Over the years I've greatly enjoyed this opportunity to get together with you, and report on the week's events here in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' said the one-time radio sportscaster and <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> actor. He started the Saturday series on April 3, 1982. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> noted that he and his wife <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> planned to return home to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> after the inauguration of President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Friday. `` We go with full hearts, with best wishes for <PERSON> George </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> and with gratitude to all of you. It's been a privilege to serve the people and the nation we've always loved, and loved so much today,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` We shared a great deal together. For me, it's been a special relationship.'' Several hours after delivering his address, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> departed for an overnight stay at the presidential retreat in Camp David. In a first, the president and his wife traveled aboard a new, $ 14 million <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON> helicopter that has been designed for presidential use. The sleek new craft is to be used for shorter distances and on international trips because it is small enough to be transported overseas in cargo aircraft. In his radio address, the president said he was n't leaving with a downcast spirit, asserting that the economy was booming, the nation's social problems were being dealt with and `` the Soviet menace shows some sign of relenting.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said his eight-year presidency was only part of `` a far larger story, the story of a people and a cause ... the hope of human freedom, the quest for it, the achievement of it, is the American saga.'' `` Whether we seek it or not, whether we like it or not, we Americans are keepers of the miracle. We are asked to be guardians of a place to come to, a place to start again, a place to live in the dignity God meant for his children. May it ever be so,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said. The president began his script with the traditional greeting, `` My fellow Americans,'' and ended it as he always has: `` Thanks for listening. And God bless you.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first job was as a sports broadcaster in <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, and radio gave him the exposure that helped him launch a career in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. As an actor-turned-politician, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> honed his radio style for use as a political tool during his days as the governor of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Over the years, it has been difficult to calculate how many people hear the president's live, noontime address, since many of the radio networks that have carried it only `` feed'' it to their subscribers, who either replay it at their leisure or do not air it at all. The only time the president was assured his voice would be carried came during the 1984 campaign, when his campaign purchased the air time. The president personally chose themes for his addresses. Occasionally, he dominated the news, as on the Saturday he used the folksy-style addresses to announce the reappointment of <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, or the time he announced suspension of a preferential trading status for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in the wake of the communist government's suppression of the Solidarity labor union. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s most infamous remarks came outside the formal radio address, when he announced prior to one speech from his ranch in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> that he had `` just signed legislation that will outlaw <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> forever. The bombing begins in five minutes.'' The president has a habit of joking with his aides prior to the talk, and the remarks were made during a voice check when the microphone was turned on but he was not yet on the air. The remarks were heard by the radio `` pool'' that was transmitting it to the other networks.
