<HEAD>Navy Reduces Persian Gulf Force Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval force in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> is being trimmed again, leaving the fleet with six surface fighting ships, the lowest number since the mid-1987 buildup that began as the Iraq-Iran war escalated. As the missile cruiser USS <PERSON> Josephus </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> and three missile frigates departed the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> in recent days, three newly arriving vessels entered the waterway to begin their three-month duty tours. The three-for-four swap effectively reduced the Gulf-based fleet from 15 to 14 ships and pared the number of surface combatants _ cruisers, destroyers and frigates _ from seven to six. The total of 14 is the lowest number of American warships in the Gulf since July 1987. It also includes six minesweepers, an amphibious landing ship that serves as their `` mother ship'' and the <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salle </LOCATION>, flagship of the Joint Task Force Middle East. Another ten ships, a battle group built around the nuclear-powered aircraft carrier <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nimitz </ORGANIZATION>, remains on station in the <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. It is to be replaced by another carrier group, headed by the USS Constellation, at the end of the month. The force inside the Gulf is slowly being reduced in strength following the Iraq-Iran cease-fire that went into effect last August. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military sources say a carrier group will be operating in the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> for the foreseeable future. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement Friday that the <PERSON> Josephus </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> was being withdrawn because it was `` no longer required to meet the threat to our forces and shipping in the region.'' In fact, the departure of the <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> did not reflect a sudden decision to reduce the force. The 8,200-ton cruiser, based at <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, was scheduled to leave the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> on Jan. 8, along with three other East Coast-based ships, the frigates <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON>, <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. As those four ships sailed out of the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> in recent days, their patrol responsibilities were taken over by the destroyer <PERSON> O'Bannon </PERSON> and the frigates <PERSON> Hawes </PERSON> and <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Wert </PERSON>, all based at <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, S.C. The frigate Klakring, originally slated for deployment along with those three, had its orders canceled in December. Officials said at the time that the resulting force reduction of one ship was seen as a `` prudent move ... considering the situation'' since the cease-fire. With the arrival of the newcomers, the mix in the Gulf includes the <LOCATION> Hawes </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Wert </PERSON> and another missile frigate, the Reid, as well as the <PERSON> O'Bannon </PERSON> and another destroyer, the <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, plus the missile cruiser <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> earlier scaled back its operations in the Gulf from direct escorting of U.S.-flagged tankers to a system of `` monitoring'' their movements from a distance. It also has curtailed air patrols and, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> on Friday, recently withdrew one of the four AWACs, or airborne surveillance aircraft, based in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> during the last year of the Iraq-Iran war. There have been no armed incidents in the Gulf since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nations-brokered </LOCATION> truce went into effect Aug. 20, and other foreign navies have been pulling out their forces. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> disclosed earlier in the week that it planned to withdraw its last three minesweepers by March, leaving it with a three-ship patrol unit. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> are withdrawing entirely, and the French have cut their regional force to reflect the reduced tensions in the waterway since the 8-year war ended. Although the cease-fire has worked, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said during a visit to the Gulf on Dec. 5 that there was `` no plan for major changes in our force structure'' as long as <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> failed to make any progress toward a negotiated peace. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have made it clear that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would continue to maintain a permanent force in the Gulf, at least at the level of four to six warships that were assigned there before the 1987 buildup. The continued presence of a Soviet fleet, some seven to ten warships, is seen as an important factor affecting the rate at which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will reduce its <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> force, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military sources say. In any case, those sources say, any cutbacks would not include the six minesweepers sent to the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> in late 1987 to deal with a growing threat of mines planted by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in shipping lanes. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials insist that a mine threat still exists, mainly in the northern Gulf, and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is still debating what to do with the wooden-hulled, Korean War vintage minesweepers.
