<HEAD>Moscow Takes Direct Control of Enclave Rocked By Ethnic Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Kremlin took direct control of a region claimed by two rival republics, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said Saturday, in the government's most determined bid to calm its worst pocket of ethnic unrest. The decree keeps the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region within the southern republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and rejects demands that it become part of the neighboring republic of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> are mainly Christian and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> is predominately Moslem. A commission led by <PERSON> Arkady </PERSON> <PERSON> Volsky </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s representative in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>'s troubled region of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, can suspend local governing councils, administrative bodies and informal organizations, and oversee the mass media, publishing, health and education, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The declaration was adopted `` in connection with the persistent strain in inter-ethnic relations in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and around it with a view to preventing their further aggravation and to stabilizing the situation in the region,'' the official news agency said. The decision was made Thursday by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's highest executive body, but released only Saturday by the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. Previous reports had said only that a `` special situation'' had been imposed on <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. The decree was billed as a temporary measure but did not say how long it will last or when new elections will be held. It did not say who besides <PERSON> Volsky </PERSON> will serve on the committee. More than 60 people have been killed and about 200,000 have fled their homes as a result of the dispute that flared up in February 1988 over control of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> have rejected annexation, and the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> instead opted for a long-term economic and social development program. But that has not stopped the unrest, which last erupted into violence in mid-November. Military rule and a strict curfew was imposed on the Armenian capital <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> capital <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, and other cities. Top Kremlin officials, including President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, have reacted angrily to demands for annexation that have continued after the Dec. 7 earthquake that devastated northern <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and killed about 25,000 people. Armenian activists say several of their leaders have been arrested and held in administrative detention. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said that under the decree the powers of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s legislature and executive bodies `` shall be suspended until the holding of elections of a new composition of the Soviet `` The committee shall be entrusted with the task of being in charge of the local bodies of state power and administration of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>,'' it said. Courts and prosecutors in the disputed territory will work under new regulations to be imposed by the procurator-general, <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The committee shall have the right to suspend the activities of public organizations and independently-acting associations if they run counter to the Constitution and legislation of the <LOCATION> U.S.S.R. </LOCATION>, or, if necessary, to dissolve them,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. That provision apparently was aimed at the informal organizations formed by activists to push demands for annexation by <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Official Azerbaijani newspapers have complained that officials in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> practically stopped obeying any orders from <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>. Lengthy strikes have been reported in the area's largest city, <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>. The latest violence erupted after reports reached <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> had sent settlers into <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> to build a factory and boost the region's ethnic Armenian majority.
