<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GINSBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> basketball coach <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> walked off the court at game time Saturday night, protesting a toughened <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> rule on scholarships, with the help of a standing ovation from fans. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s dramatic gesture came just before the tipoff of Saturday night's Big East men's basketball game between his seventh-ranked <ORGANIZATION> Hoyas </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. As he headed for the dressing room, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> did not openly acknowledge the cheering crowd at Capital Centre. He went to his car and drove away without speaking to reporters. Assistant coach <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> took over, and the game continued. The move was to protest a new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collegiate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> rule that will impose harsher academic requirements for incoming freshmen to qualify for athletic scholarships. After being defeated Tuesday, the proposal passed Wednesday by a 163-154 vote at the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> convention in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Without being specific, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said Friday that his boycott would continue `` until I am satisfied that something has been done.'' He called the new rule `` a tremendous tragedy'' because of its potential effect on the ability of poor youths to get a college education. Proposal 42, which is to go into effect next year, would prevent high school students who meet only part of the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION>'s entrance standards from being eligible for an athletic scholarship their first year in college. It applies to athletes who fail to get both a `` C'' average in 11 key subjects in high school and a minimum score on one of two standardized college entrance tests: either a 700 out of a possible 1,600 on the Scholastic Aptitude Test or a 15 out of 36 on the American College Test. A previous rule allowed those who met either of the two standards to get a scholarship, though they could n't play on a team as freshmen. Figures released in 1987 put the nationwide average SAT score at 906 and the average ACT score at 18.7. Critics have charged that the tests are biased abainst minorities, who tend to score lower than whites. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, who is black, purposely refused to label the proposal as racist, but did call it `` discriminatory.'' `` I'm beginning to feel that a kid with a low socio-economic background has been invited to dinner, had dessert and is now being asked to leave,'' he said. Temple basketball coach <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, one of many college coaches who expressed support for <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, said, `` Instead of considering some of these proposals, they plan to punish the youngsters, punish these kids who come from a poor background and have a poor educational opportunity.'' But <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Cawood </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> assistant executive director, said in a statement that those who voted for the rule considered it `` a means to strengthen the academic entrance requirements for freshmen,'' not a racial issue. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> is one of the country's top college basketball coaches. He was coach of the 1988 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> men's basketball team, which won the bronze medal, and in 1984 his <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> team won the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> championship. <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> coach <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> applauded <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s action, saying his lofty stature among coaches helps make it a very effective demonstration. `` I do n't think that just saying anything gets it done,'' <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. `` In his position, by doing what he's doing, he will draw more attention to it. He feels something needs to be done right now.''
