<HEAD>Baghdad Sheraton Goes On The Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Saturday offered one of its major hotels, the <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> Sheraton, for sale to the private sector. State-run newspapers carried an advertisement offering the 307-room hotel to a private company with at least $ 150 million in capital. The hotel is wholly owned by the government and run by the international Sheraton chain. The ruling <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in September abolished the state tourism authority and decided to sell all of its assets, including five major hotels in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. The move to sell tourist facilities is a part of President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s drive to develop the private sector in what has been a staunch socialist economy. Selling state assets is seen as a means of overcoming massive government debts and stimulating the economy battered by the 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that ended with a cease-fire in August. The Sheraton chain runs another hotel in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s southern port of <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION> that was badly damaged by Iranian shelling. Sheraton officials said they have no idea whether it was also up for sale, but they confirmed the government has announced it would be on the market soon.
