<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A barge slammed into a concrete pillar supporting the center of the three-mile <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> on Saturday, knocking the pillar into the water and halting vehicle and marine traffic, officials said. The four-lane bridge was clear of traffic at the time and no injuries were reported. The bridge is the only direct link between <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> and suburban Gulf Breeze and is used daily by thousands of commuters. The only other land access is a detour of about 60 miles. The bridge will remain closed to all boat and vehicular traffic for three weeks while the southbound lanes are stabilized, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazucha </PERSON>, regional maintenance engineer for the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>. Two-lane traffic then will be permitted in the northbound lanes while permanent repairs are made, which will take from four to six months, <PERSON> Hazucha </PERSON> said. Construction workers building an emergency lane on the bridge `` saw the situation coming and cleared the site so there were no cars actually traveling over that spot,'' said Gulf Breeze City Manager <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON>. `` Fortunately, obviously, there were no vehicles that went into the water.'' Officials said it was not immediately known why the barge was unable to navigate away from the pillar. <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> Boling </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Esther </PERSON>, said he was fishing on the end of the Gulf Breeze pier next to the bridge Saturday morning when the barge hit about 100 feet away. `` I just stood here and watched him take out the end of the bridge,'' <PERSON> Boling </PERSON> said. `` They scared the fish away.'' Initial reports indicated the southbound side of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>