 A West German company that <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> officials contend exported goods to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> to help it build a suspected chemical weapons plant is being investigated by a <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> prosecutor. The new probe compounds official embarrassment over a scandal that has dominated West German politics for two weeks. The <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s vice chairman, <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, called Friday for a federal criminal probe. Government officials conceded Friday they had received intelligence reports in October that indicated German companies may have helped build the plant in <LOCATION> Rabta </LOCATION>, about 40 miles outside the Libyan capital of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>.
