<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv14-15   01-14 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 14-15,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Experts Predicting Record-level Volume For 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Throughout the country, aging bridges crack or sway as traffic clogs pot-hole-ridden roads and highways. Public dams and sewers cry out for more than a good plumbing job. Then there's the problem of trashing our trash ... As the nation's infrastructure and public works systems show increasing signs of deterioration, many public officials are expected to turn more and more to bonds. At least that's what experts predicted this past week at a forum by <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading insurer of municipal bonds. `` There's no way of escaping those needs. You've got to get to work,'' said forum participant <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koenen </PERSON>, managing director for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` I'm very bullish on volume.'' An MBIA survey of municipal bond professionals predicted that volume of tax-exempt municipal bonds _ most often used to finance infrastructure and other public projects _ will rise 7 percent in 1989 to a record level $ 120 billion. Volume for the taxable municipal market should reach $ 2.8 billion this year, compared with an estimated $ 2.2 billion in 1988, it said. The survey suggested the biggest increase would come in bond issues for transportation, estimating a 61 percent rise in volume over last year to $ 14.08 billion. However, the biggest chunk of newly issued bonds, an estimated $ 30.04 billion this year vs. $ 28.38 billion in 1988, will be used to refund old debt, the survey said. It predicted a 58 percent rise for gas and electric to $ 12.14 billion; a 48 percent rise for water and sewer projects to $ 12.67 billion; a 35 percent rise for hospitals to $ 14.94 billion; a 26 percent rise for education to $ 20.31 billion; and just a fractional rise in housing to $ 13.96 billion. In last year's general election alone voters nationwide approved a record $ 13.8 billion in state and local bond issues to finance projects ranging from road and bridge repairs to new prison facilities. Experts say the anticipated increase in bond volume is largely due to a steady reduction of federal assistance and the historical neglect of public works projects by some local and state governments. `` Until very recently ... the need to replenish and expand public works has been largely ignored,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, senior director of the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, noted in a separate report on infrastructure needs and financing released at the forum. `` By the early 1980s, the infrastructure was wearing out faster than it was being replaced,'' he said. Last year, one of the nation's busiest bridges _ the <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION>, which links <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> _ was shut down for more than three months after inspectors discovered extensive corrosion. The bridge was built in 1903 for bicycles and horse-drawn buggies. When closed it was carrying more than 100,000 vehicles and 420 trains daily. <PERSON> Koenen </PERSON> noted that just a few weeks ago, the 122-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Roebling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suspension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bridge </ORGANIZATION>, which spans the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, was closed briefly after it began swaying under heavy pedestrian traffic following the Bengals-Seahawks football game. But officials later declared the bridge safe. Supporting the <ORGANIZATION> MBIA </ORGANIZATION> survey on projected volume, <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>'s study found that capital investment needs are by far the greatest in the areas of highways, streets and bridges. Next to that comes public transit, water supply and distribution, waste water treatment, solid waste disposal and airports. <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> also noted that changing population patterns will affect municipal bond issuance. `` If the population trend continues, 62 percent of the population will live in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and West by 2010, compared with 48 percent in the 1970s,'' he said. `` That's going to stimulate spending needs.'' Another factor that could effect future municipal spending is the so-called `` Greenhouse Effect,'' or the pollution-caused warming of the atmosphere, <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> said. `` Recent studies indicate that global warming, with the resulting rise in water levels due to polar melting, will affect economic activity and infrastructure spending in coastal areas.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15</NOTE>
