<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15</HEAD>
<HEAD>1988 Futures Volume Set New Record; Drought Boosted Ag Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Trading volume on the nation's futures exchanges rose by a modest 7.3 percent last year as a drought-driven surge in agricultural hedging and speculation helped offset a slump in the stock-index futures markets. Volume on the 11 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> futures exchanges totaled a record 295 million contracts, compared with 275 million contracts traded in 1987, according to figures compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group. The increase compares with volume expansion of nearly 25 percent in 1987 and continues a growth pattern of more than two decades. On futures exchanges, people trade contracts for future deliveries of commodities _ such as grain, cattle, gold and crude oil _ and financial instruments, including government securities, stocks and foreign currencies. Commercial players _ those directly involved in producing, buying or selling a particular commodity or financial instrument _ use futures to hedge against losses in their business dealings or financial investments. Speculators are investors who seek to profit from the fluctuating prices of the contracts. Agricultural futures trading in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dates back more than 120 years but financial futures, introduced in the early 1970s, now account for most trades. Last year, financial futures trading accounted for 139.1 million, or nearly 57 percent, of the total futures volume, <ORGANIZATION> FIA </ORGANIZATION> figures show. More than half of those trades involved the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond contract, with a volume of 70.3 million, a 5.2 percent increase over the previous year. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, the oldest and largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> futures exchange, also reported a dramatic resurgence in grain and soybean futures trading. Wheat volume soared by 75 percent, soybean trading jumped 69 percent, and corn volume surged 53 percent as the worst drought in 50 years withered crops and sent prices skyrocketing. `` The drought of 1988 added significant increases to volume in agricultural trading,'' said <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON>, the exchange's chairman He said the exchange's more lightly traded agricultural options, hedging instruments that are similar to futures, also `` worked extremely well to manage risk in the agricultural markets.'' Overall volume at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> grew by 12.5 percent in 1988, the 20th consecutive year of record volume for the exchange. With a total of 143.1 million futures and options contracts traded, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s share of the industry was 48.5 percent. The nation's second-largest futures exchange, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, did not fare as well. Officials reported a 7.5 percent decrease in volume, mainly due to a 40 percent drop in stock-index futures trading at the exchange. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trades the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 stock-index futures contract, by far the industry's leading contract of its type despite the drop in volume. Officials blamed the decline on slack interest in stock market investing following the crash of October 1987. But the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> also reported a 6.6 percent increase in foreign currency futures trading, including a 6.3 percent gain in its Eurodollar futures contract _ the exchange's volume leader _ and a 20 percent leap in yen futures Overall volume at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> last year totaled 78 million contracts, giving the exchange a 26.4 percent share of the industry. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, home of crude-oil and platinum futures, scored a 33.5 percent volume increase with 34.3 million contracts traded. The volume placed the exchange third in the industry with an 11.6 percent share. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which specializes in gold, silver and copper, saw its volume shrink by 10 percent to 19.2 million for a 6.5 percent share of the industry. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> traded a record 10 million contracts, up from 6.3 million in 1988, for a 3.4 percent share. Trading volume at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> MidAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> reached a record 3.4 million contracts, a 44 gain over 1987, giving the exchange a 1.2 percent share of the industry. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> reported a record turnover of 3.1 million cotton, orange-juice and financial futures contracts, a 19 percent gain, for a 1 percent share of the industry. The remaining 1.4 percent of the industry volume was divided among the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Minneapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. These figures do not include statistics from the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which trades only financial options.
</TEXT>
