<FIRST>d f PM-OilPrices     01-14 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Indications that world oil production is declining helped strengthen some crude oil prices this week. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> said Friday the cartel's output for January could fall below the 18.5 million barrel-a-day target. In addition, ongoing problems in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> have reduced oil production by about 500,000 barrels a day. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the February contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 31 cents to close at $ 18.48 a barrel Friday after advancing 3 cents on Thursday. The contract traded as high as $ 18.64 but retreated on profit-taking, analysts said. Other contract months were mixed. However, traders noted that prices of crude contracts between June and November fell. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s accord took effect Jan. 1 and extends for six months. Many economists speculate that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> will raise its volume in the second half of the year. WTI was trading in the $ 15 range when members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> agreed in November to cut back production to 18.5 million barrels. Traders say prices have risen amid signs <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> is abiding by the agreement and new speculation on Friday encouraged further buying. `` A statement from Subroto that January production would be below the quota was probably the main factor moving the market,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Byers </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline futures rose. The February contract for gasoline closed 0.70 cent higher at 49.97 cents a gallon. Heating oil futures ended the day mixed, with the February contract up 0.11 cent at 52.95 cents a gallon. The March contract also rose, but subsequent months declined. Heating oil prices have not firmed along with other energy prices recently as demand has fallen off due to seasonal factors, traders said.
</TEXT>
